<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41017e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41017e">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41017e"> 17(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> puts ear to cunt / <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font>(hear twins talking)<font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> &amp; runs away</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> The &ldquo;Bahalul&rdquo; of D&apos;Herbelot. This worthy was a half-witted Sage (like the lourodivi of Russia and the Irish Omadhaun) who occupies his own place in contemporary histories, flourished under Harun al-Rashid and still is famous in Persian Story. When the Caliph married him perforce and all the ceremonies were duly performed and he was bedded with the bride, he applied his <mark>ear to her privities and forthwith ran away</mark> with the utmost speed and alarm. They brought him back and questioned him concerning his conduct when he made answer, &ldquo;If you had only <mark>heard what it said to me</mark> you would have done likewise.&rdquo; <small> Richard F. Burton, trans. <a name="RBTE3" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE3"><cite title="source">Supplemental Nights to the Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) VII, 155n3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: addition in bk ink </mm> </dd></dl>
